[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering focuses on building software products and looks at all the activities involved in developing a software system from initial idea to final product.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In contrast, software engineering focuses on building software products. It looks at all the activities involved in developing a software system from initial idea to final product.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering design concepts tend to focus on general-purpose design principles, patterns, and criteria, and present design and analysis techniques that scale to large software systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "software engineering design concepts tend to focus on general-purpose design principles, patterns, and criteria; advanced courses present design and analysis techniques that scale to large software systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "At its core, computer science focuses on data, data transformation, and algorithms, and advanced courses present designs and programming techniques for specific application domains.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "At its core, computer science focuses on data, data transformation, and algorithms; advanced courses present designs and programming techniques for specific application domains.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering is more general, more applied, and has a broader scope than computer science.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "As such, software engineering is more general, is more applied, and has a broader scope than computer science.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Software engineering borrows and adapts principles and practices from engineering that scale to large systems and aim at producing successful products, including early planning to reveal errors early, systematic and predictable design and development processes, and consideration of nonfunctional properties such as performance, maintainability, usability, economy, and time-to-market.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "From engineering, a software engineering curriculum borrows and adapts principles and practices that scale to large systems and that are aimed at producing successful products: - Early planning and development activities that help to reveal errors early in the development process, when they are cheaper and easier to fix - Systematic, predictable design and development processes that help to ensure that a software product is developed economically and that it is fit for use - Consideration of nonfunctional properties, such as performance, maintainability, usability, economy, and time-to-market, that often determine whether a software product is acceptable",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Unlike traditional engineering disciplines that produce physical artifacts obeying physical laws, software engineering produces software artifacts deployed on computers that obey the laws and limits of computing, which makes software design and testing often far more difficult.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "whereas most engineers produce physical artifacts that are deployed in the real world and obey physical laws, software engineers produce software artifacts that are deployed on computers (which are artificial worlds) and obey the laws and limits of computing. Most noticeably, a physical artifact has continuous behavior, which means that we can test the product in one situation and extrapolate how it will behave in related situations. Software artifacts cannot exhibit continuous behavior, which means that similar inputs may result in wildly different output values. Also, software is implemented using discrete-valued variables, and the imprecision introduced by such variables can accumulate in long computations.'Off by one' errors in other engineering disciplines are inconsequential, but such errors in software are disastrous. Thus, many of the traditional modeling and evaluation techniques in the engineer's standard toolkit are inappropriate for software. Software's flexibility and malleability belie its complexity; even small changes can have large effects, so design and testing are often far more difficult than in other engineering domains.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality focuses on the products and processes, measured with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing, emphasizing the technical value of the products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When the focus of quality assessment is on products and processes, we usually measure quality with mathematical expressions involving faults, failures, and timing. Rarely is the scope broadened to include a business perspective, where quality is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded. That is, we look at the technical value of our products, rather than more broadly at their business value, and we make decisions based only on the resulting products' technical quality.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality, on the other hand, considers the products and services in the context of the business environment, focusing on the business value rather than just technical metrics.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "quality is viewed in terms of the products and services being provided by the business in which the software is embedded. That is, we look at the technical value of our products, rather than more broadly at their business value, and we make decisions based only on the resulting products' technical quality.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Technical quality is important because it measures operational performance, such as uptime, maintenance costs, and costs connected with modifications, which are essential for managing development effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We measure the quality [of our software] by the obvious metrics: up versus down time, maintenance costs, costs connected with modifications, and the like. In other words, we manage development based on operational performance within cost parameters.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Business quality is important because it ensures that the software delivers clear and expected business value, which is crucial for making informed business decisions and justifying investments in software development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If there is not clear (expected) business value (expressed quantitatively: number of claims proces",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software occur when the software does not perform as required by the specifications, which can be due to faults in requirements, design, or implementation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "What do we mean when we say that our software has failed? Usually,we mean that the software does not do what the requirements describe.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Examples of failures include a system responding to unauthorized users due to incorrect or incomplete requirements, faults in system design that make certain functionalities impossible, or faults in program design such as incorrect access control algorithms.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, the specification may state that the system must respond to a particular query only when the user is authorized to see the data. If the program responds to an unauthorized user, we say that the system has failed.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The system design may contain a fault. Perhaps the database and query-language designs make it impossible to authorize users.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The program design may contain a fault. The component descriptions may contain an access control algorithm that does not handle this case correctly.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Such failures affect the quality of the software product by causing it to behave incorrectly or insecurely, which can lead to loss of user trust, security breaches, or system crashes.",
        "citations": []
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures in software occur due to faults and errors introduced during various stages of software development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A fault occurs when a human makes a mistake, called an error, in performing some software activity.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Faults can arise from misunderstandings in requirements, design errors, or incorrect implementation in code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, a designer may misunderstand a requirement and create a design that does not match the actual intent of the requirements analyst and the user. This design fault is an encoding of the error, and it can lead to other faults, such as incorrect code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Common types of faults in program code include algorithmic faults such as branching too soon or too late, testing for the wrong condition, forgetting to initialize variables, or forgetting to test for a particular condition.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Typical algorithmic faults include branching too soon, branching too late, testing for the wrong condition, forgetting to initialize variables or set loop invariants, forgetting to test for a particular condition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Failures result from one or more faults in the system design, program design, or program code.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The system design may contain a fault. Perhaps the database and query-language designs make it impossible to authorize users. The program design may contain a fault. The component descriptions may contain an access control algorithm that does not handle this case correctly. The program code may be wrong. It may implement the algorithm improperly or incompletely.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Testing is used to discover faults by creating conditions where the code does not react as planned, and a test is considered successful only when a fault is discovered or a failure occurs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We test a program to demonstrate the existence of a fault. Because our goal is to discover faults, we consider a test successful only when a fault is discovered or a failure occurs as a result of our testing procedures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The older issues of software magazines such as IEEE Computer and IEEE Software from the 1970s and 1980s often focused on foundational and emerging software engineering challenges, including software certification, licensing, and the legal and ethical responsibilities when software fails.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Kaner and Pels (1998) consider who is responsible when software fails, and what you can do as a consumer when your software product does not work properly.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Other excellent references related to software certification and licensing include Allen and Hawthorn (1999), Canadian Engineering Quality Board (2001), Knight and Leveson (1986), Notkin (2000), Parnas (2000), and Shaw (1990).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These older issues also discussed the development of software engineering as a discipline, including the role of ethics and personal responsibility in software development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An excellent discussion of ethics and the role of personal responsibility can be found in Baase (2002).",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Shaw, Mary (1990). 'Prospects for an engineering discipline of software.' IEEE Software , 7(6) (November): 15-24.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, more recent issues of these magazines tend to focus on practical software engineering practices and technology adoption, such as reviews and inspections, incremental development, user involvement, automated revision control, and component-based development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The January/February 2000 issue of IEEE Software contains an editorial by McConnell about software engineering's best influences: reviews and inspections, information hiding, incremental development, user involvement, automated revision control, development using the Internet, programming languages: Fortran, COBOL, Turbo Pascal, Visual Basic, Capability Maturity Model for software, component-based development, metrics and measurement.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Recent discussions also include technology transfer, group decision-making models, and the social aspects of software engineering.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The social science literature is rich with information about group decisionmaking. Klein (1998) is a very readable introduction to the recognition-primed decision model. The January/February 2000 issue of IEEE Software addresses the more general question of what we can learn from other disciplines.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Riddle (1985) paper remains the most comprehensive survey on software technology use to date. The U.S. Software Engineering Institute has published several technical reports on technology transfer.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The process of getting ready for class or work in the morning can be described as a sequence of activities that transition from one state to another, similar to the process of starting a car as shown in the transition diagrams.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Transition diagrams supplement the process model by showing how the states are related to one another. For example, Figure 2.12 illustrates the transitions for a car.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A typical morning preparation process might include the following steps: waking up, getting out of bed, personal hygiene (such as brushing teeth and washing face), dressing up, having breakfast, and finally leaving for class or work.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This process can be captured in a transition diagram or an activity diagram, where each state or activity leads to the next, and decisions or conditions can be represented by decision nodes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can use activity diagrams to model the flow of procedures or activities in a class.When conditions are used to decide which activity to invoke, a decision node represents the choices.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
