[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The process of getting a degree (bachelor's, master's, or PhD) can be described as a work breakdown structure consisting of phases, steps, and activities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Analysis of this kind is sometimes described as generating a work breakdown structure for a given project, because it depicts the project as a set of discrete pieces of work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, the phases could be: 1) Admission and Enrollment, 2) Coursework, 3) Research (for master's and PhD), 4) Thesis/Dissertation Writing, and 5) Graduation.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Each phase can be broken down into steps and activities. For instance, Coursework may include attending lectures, completing assignments, and passing exams. Research may include literature review, experiments or data collection, and analysis.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Then, we break each phase into smaller steps, such as clearing and grubbing, seeding the turf, and planting trees and shrubs. Where necessary, we can divide the steps into activities; for example, finishing the interior involves completing the interior plumbing, interior electrical work, wallboard, interior painting, floor covering, doors, and fixtures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Each activity has parameters such as precursor (what must be completed before it starts), duration, due date, and endpoint (milestone).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can describe each activity with four parameters: the precursor, duration, due date, and endpoint. A precursor is an event or set of events that must occur before the activity can begin; it describes the set of conditions that allows the activity to begin; ... Signifying that the activity has ended, the endpoint is usually a milestone or",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An activity graph for the degree process would show activities as nodes or bars with dependencies (precursors) indicated by arrows. For example, Enrollment must precede Coursework, which must precede Research, which must precede Thesis Writing, which must precede Graduation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A project's work breakdown structure gives no indication of the interdependence of the work units or of the parts of the project that can be developed concurrently.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Critical path analysis of a project schedule tells us who must wait for what as the project is being developed. It also tells us which activities must be completed on schedule to avoid delay.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The critical path is the sequence of activities that must be completed on schedule to avoid delaying the entire degree process. For example, if Coursework is delayed, Research and subsequent Thesis Writing and Graduation will also be delayed.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Critical path analysis of a project schedule tells us who must wait for what as the project is being developed. It also tells us which activities must be completed on schedule to avoid delay.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The organizational structure for a software development or maintenance project depends on factors such as the number of people on the team, the backgrounds and work styles of the team members, and the management styles of the customers and developers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The choice of an appropriate structure for your project depends on several things: the backgrounds and work styles of the team members, the number of people on the team, the management styles of the customers and developers",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One popular organizational structure is the chief programmer team, where one person is totally responsible for the system's design and development, and all other team members report to this chief programmer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One popular organizational structure is the chief programmer team, first used at IBM (Baker 1972). On a chief programmer team, one person is totally responsible for a system's design and development. All other team members report to the chief programmer, who has the final say on every decision.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The chief programmer supervises all others, designs all programs, and assigns code development to other team members. An understudy substitutes for the chief when necessary, and a librarian maintains project documentation, compiles and links code, and performs preliminary testing.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The chief programmer supervises all others, designs all programs, and assigns the code development to the other team members. Assisting the chief is an understudy, whose principal job is substituting for the chief programmer when necessary. A librarian assists the team, responsible for maintaining all project documentation. The librarian also compiles and links the code, and performs preliminary testing of all modules submitted to the library.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project by placing all responsibility for decisions with the chief programmer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Regarding work styles, people differ in how they communicate and make decisions. Some are extroverts who tell others their thoughts, while others are introverts who ask for suggestions before forming opinions. Decision styles vary from intuitive (based on feelings) to rational (based on facts).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When communicating ideas, some people tell others their thoughts, and some people ask for suggestions from others before forming an opinion. Jung (1959) calls the former extroverts and the latter introverts. Similarly, intuitive people base their decisions on feelings about and emotional reactions to a problem. Others are rational, deciding primarily by examining the facts and carefully considering all options.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For example, intuitive employees may prefer design and development tasks requiring new ideas, while rational employees may prefer maintenance programming requiring attention to detail and analysis.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Work styles can also involve choice of worker for a given task. For instance, intuitive employees may prefer design and development (requiring new ideas) to maintenance programming and design (requiring attention to detail and analysis of complex results).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Advantages of the chief programmer team structure include:",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Clear responsibility and decision-making authority centralized in the chief programmer.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One person is totally responsible for a system's design and development. All other team members report to the chief programmer, who has the final say on every decision.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Minimized communication overhead among team members.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By placing all responsibility for all decisions with the chief programmer, the team structure minimizes the amount of communication needed during the project.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Allows programmers to focus on programming by delegating documentation and preliminary testing to the librarian.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "This division of labor allows the programmers to focus on what they do best: programming.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Potential problems with this structure may arise if the chief programmer becomes a bottleneck or if communication is insufficient among team members, especially in projects with high uncertainty or changing requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Researchers continue to investigate how project team structure affects the resulting product and how to choose the most appropriate organization in a given situation. A National Science Foundation (1983) investigation found that projects with a high degree of certainty, stability, uniformity, and repetition can be accomplished more effectively by a hierarchical organizational structure such as the chief programmer team. These projects require little communication among project members, so they are well-suited to an organization that stresses rules, specialization, formality, and a clear definition of organizational hierarchy. On the other hand, when there is much uncertainty involved in a project, a more democratic approach may be better.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two techniques for making a prediction for effort are expert judgment and analogy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many effort-estimation methods rely on expert judgment. Some are informal techniques, based on a manager's experience with similar projects.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Expert judgment involves making an educated guess about the effort needed to build an entire system or its subsystems, based on the competence, experience, objectivity, and perception of the estimator.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In its simplest form, such an estimate makes an educated guess about the effort needed to build an entire system or its subsystems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Analogy is used to estimate effort by comparing the proposed system to a similar system that has already been built, assuming that the cost to produce the new system should be similar to the cost of the existing one.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Many times analogies are used to estimate effort. If we have already built a system much like the one proposed, then we can use the similarity as the basis for our estimates.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Effort estimation must be done as early as possible during the project's life cycle because it affects resource allocation and project feasibility.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Cost, schedule, and effort estimation must be done as early as possible during the project's life cycle, since it affects resource allocation and project feasibility.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, estimation should be repeated throughout the life cycle to refine the estimate based on more complete information about the project's characteristics.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "But estimation should be done repeatedly throughout the life cycle; as aspects of the project change, the estimate can be refined, based on more complete information about the project's characteristics.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Two values that can be calculated from the estimate (E) and the actual value (A) to help determine the accuracy of the estimating process are the acceptance range and predictive validity.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We describe this window by using an acceptance range : a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value. Thus, 20% is the model's acceptance range.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The acceptance range is defined as the maximum difference allowed between the prediction and the actual value. For example, if the acceptance range is 20%, the predicted value is considered acceptable if it is within 20% of the actual value.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We describe this window by using an acceptance range : a statement of the maximum difference between prediction and actual value. Thus, 20% is the model's acceptance range.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Predictive validity is a measure of how well the prediction corresponds to the actual outcomes. It is used to assess the accuracy of prediction models, with higher predictive validity indicating better accuracy.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Discriminant analysis, Results of Comparing Prediction Models (Lanubile 1996) ©1996 IEEE.Predictive Validity = p = 0.621.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The acceptance range helps determine if a prediction is acceptable by setting a threshold for the maximum allowable error between the estimate and the actual value. Predictive validity provides a statistical measure of the prediction's accuracy, helping to compare different prediction models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Depending on the circumstances, we may find a large window too wide to be useful; for instance, the window may be too large for effective maintenance planning. Other managers may feel comfortable with a large acceptance range, given the uncertainties of software development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One size measure in object-oriented (OO) systems is counting objects and methods as a basic size measure.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Pfleeger (1991) used objects and methods as a basic size measure in her effort-estimation approach",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The advantage of this measure is that it allows estimation techniques to be reapplied during development and the estimate inputs are directly comparable, making it easy to track size growth over the product's life.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The advantage of assessing size in the same terms throughout development is clear: the estimation technique can be reapplied during development, and the estimate inputs are directly comparable. In other words, it is easy to see what the initial size is, and to track its growth over the product's life.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "However, the context does not explicitly mention disadvantages of this measure.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Another size measure described by Lorenz and Kidd (1994) involves counting the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in use cases, which reflects the product in terms of its use cases and scenarios.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Lorenz and Kidd count the number of scenario scripts (NSS) in the use cases. They report that this measure is correlated with application size and number of test cases.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "sentence",
        "segment": "The advantages of NSS are that it can feed an estimation model for predicting project effort or duration and helps the test team prepare test cases and allocate resources for future testing activities.",
        "citations": [
