[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Robertsons' requirements definition template, available at http://www.systemsguild.com, is a comprehensive tool designed to assist software developers in eliciting and checking a set of requirements effectively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com.This template is accompanied by a description of the Volere process model, which is a complete process for eliciting and checking a set of requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template is particularly helpful during the requirements elicitation and validation phases, where it guides developers in confirming that the proposed functions and constraints accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We review the proposed functions and constraints, to confirm that they accurately reflect the customer's needs and intentions.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "To use the template effectively for validating requirements, the following activities are necessary:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Review the proposed functions and constraints with representatives to ensure they are realistic and within development capabilities.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our representatives review the proposed functions and constraints, to confirm that they are realistic and within our development abilities.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Check all requirements for omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistency.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All requirements are checked again for omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistency.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Assess and document any risks involved in development or system functioning, discuss alternatives, and agree on approaches.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If any risk is involved in the development or in the actual functioning of the system, we can assess and document this risk, discuss and compare alternatives, and come to some agreement on the approaches to be used.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Plan for testing the system by deciding how requirements will be revalidated, who will provide test data, and which requirements will be tested in which phases.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We can talk about testing the system: how the requirements will be revalidated as the requirements grow and change; who will provide test data to the test team; which requirements will be tested in which phases, if the system is to be developed in phases.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Developers using the template must possess skills in communication and collaboration to work effectively with customers and users, analytical skills to identify and resolve conflicts or misunderstandings, and familiarity with validation techniques and tools that support consistency and completeness checking.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our choice of validation technique depends on the experience and preferences of the stakeholders and on the technique's appropriateness for the notations used in the requirements definition. Some notations have tool support for checking consistency and completeness. There are also tools that can help with the review process and with tracking problems and their resolutions.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Whenever a problem is identified, the problem is documented, its cause is determined, and the requirements analysts are charged with the task of fixing the problem.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The template helps uncover various types of errors and faults, including misunderstandings about function outputs, conflicts in data representation preferences, unrealistic reliability or availability goals, omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistencies in the requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For example, validation may reveal that there is a great misunderstanding about the way in which a certain function will produce results. The customers may require data to be reported in miles, whereas the users want the data in kilometers. The customers may set a reliability or availability goal that developers deem impossible to meet. These conflicts need to be resolved before design can begin.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "All requirements are checked again for omissions, incompleteness, and inconsistency.",
