]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Pamela Zave proposed a classification scheme for organizing different types of research in software requirements engineering, which helps in structuring and understanding the diverse research efforts in this field.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Pamela Zave has proposed a classification scheme for organizing the different types of research that go on in the area of software requirements (P. Zave (1997). “Classification of research efforts in requirements engineering.” ACM Computing Surveys, 29(4): 315 - 321).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One category of research in requirements engineering focuses on eliciting, representing, and validating requirements, which is crucial for software developers because it ensures that the system built meets the users' needs and functions correctly. This research helps developers understand system intent and function, resolve conflicting requirements, and document relationships among requirements, which ultimately leads to building software that satisfies customer goals and reduces costly errors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In this chapter, we look at the various types of requirements and their different sources, and we discuss how to resolve conflicting requirements. We detail a variety of modeling notations and requirements-specification methods, with examples of both automated and manual techniques. These models help us understand the requirements and document the relationships among them.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Analyzing requirements involves much more than merely writing down what the customer wants. As we shall see, we must find requirements on which both we and the customer can agree and on which we can build our test procedures.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "An example of research in this category is the work by James and Suzanne Robertson, who developed a comprehensive requirements-definition template and the Volere process model for eliciting and checking requirements. Their research addresses the problem of systematically capturing and validating requirements to ensure completeness and correctness, providing software developers with practical tools and processes to improve requirements quality and project success.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A comprehensive requirements-definition template developed by James and Suzanne Robertson can be found at the Web site of the Atlantic Systems Guild: http:// www.systemsguild.com. This template is accompanied by a description of the Volere process model, which is a complete process for eliciting and checking a set of requirements.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “InventorySearchByID” is likely to have a high degree of cohesion because it performs a single function: searching the records in inventory for matching ID numbers and returning the matching records.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Our ideal is functional cohesion , where two conditions hold: all elements essential to a single function are contained in one module, and all of that module's elements are essential to the performance of that function. A functionally cohesive module performs only the function for which it is designed, and nothing else.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “ProcessPurchase” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it performs multiple unrelated functions: removing the purchased product from inventory, printing a receipt, and updating the log.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module that serves multiple purposes is at greater risk of its elements needing to evolve in different ways or at different rates. For example, a module that encompasses both data and routines for displaying those data may change frequently and may grow in different directions, as new uses of the data require both new functions to manipulate data and new ways of visualizing them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Module “FindSet” is likely to have a low degree of cohesion because it combines different functions: processing the user's request, determining the set of matching items, and formatting the items for display, which are distinct activities that may evolve separately.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A module that serves multiple purposes is at greater risk of its elements needing to evolve in different ways or at different rates. For example, a module that encompasses both data and routines for displaying those data may change frequently and may grow in different directions, as new uses of the data require both new functions to manipulate data and new ways of visualizing them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To say that a design review should be “egoless” means that the review process is not about placing blame on a particular developer when faults or failures are discovered, but rather about correcting the faults collaboratively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When a fault is discovered or a failure occurs, the egoless development team is concerned with correcting the fault, not with placing blame on a particular developer.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Egoless reviews are necessary because they help remove personal feelings from the testing and review process, allowing for more objective identification and correction of faults.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Even when a system is developed with an egoless approach, we sometimes have difficulty removing our personal feelings from the testing process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Egoless reviews encourage shared responsibility among all participants, which forces everyone to scrutinize every design detail carefully.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "By participating in the review, they assume equal responsibility for the design with the designers themselves. This shared responsibility forces all in the review process to scrutinize every design detail.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Steps that may help achieve egoless reviews include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Using an independent test team to test the system, which helps avoid conflicts between personal responsibility and fault discovery.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, we often use an independent test team to test a system. In this way, we avoid conflict between personal responsibility for faults and the need to discover as many faults as possible.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Having the independent test team participate in requirements and design reviews, test code components individually, and test the system as it is integrated.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Furthermore, an independent test team can participate in reviewing the components throughout development. The team can be part of the requirements and design reviews, can test the code components individually, and can test the system as it is integrated and presented to the customers for acceptance.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Conducting active design reviews where reviewers use the design document in practical ways and answer questions relevant to their roles, which encourages objective evaluation.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An active design review (Parnas and Weiss 1985) is a particularly effective method for evaluating the quality of the SAD and determining whether it contains the right information. In an active review, reviewers exercise the design document by using it in ways that developers will use the final document in practice.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A software system I use is an image-processing application that allows users to apply various operations to modify their pictures, such as rotation, color tinting, and cropping.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "(c) image-processing software that allows users to apply various operations to modify their pictures (e.g., rotation, color tinting, cropping)",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One feature of the interface I dislike is the complexity and unintuitive placement of some editing tools, which makes it difficult to quickly find and use certain functions.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "This problem could have been avoided during the design process by using user interface prototyping, which involves building small versions of the system to help users identify key requirements and provide feedback iteratively.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "User Interface Prototyping. Prototyping means building a small version of a system, usually with limited functionality, that can be used to help the user or customer identify the key requirements of a system ... Often, the prototyping process is iterative: We build a prototype, evaluate it (with user and customer feedback), consider how changes might improve the product or design, and then build another prototype.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In particular, iterative prototyping would have allowed the design team to surface issues and assumptions about the interface, improving usability before finalizing the design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Since the user interface is, in a sense, a bridge between the application domain and the software development team, prototyping can bring to the surface issues and assumptions that may not have been clear using other approaches to requirements analysis.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "A well-known source that deals with design patterns in more detail is the collection presented by Gamma et al. (1995).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The collection presented by Gamma et al. (1995) is a good place to start. These patterns document design experience that can be studied in isolation. Each pattern can be adapted for reuse in new contexts.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "One of the patterns presented is the Template Method pattern. This pattern aims to reduce the amount of duplicate code among subclasses by defining the skeleton of an algorithm in a method, deferring some steps to subclasses.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "## Template Method Pattern The Template Method pattern aims to reduce the amount of duplicate code among subcla",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Template Method pattern is useful when you have multiple subclasses that share a common algorithm structure but differ in some steps. It allows subclasses to redefine certain steps of the algorithm without changing its overall structure.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The effect of using this pattern on the rest of the program is improved modularity and reduced code duplication, making the design easier to maintain and extend.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, using design patterns in practice can introduce some difficulties. Because patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, they can sometimes seem overly complicated. This added complexity may impact performance and ease of development.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Design patterns make substantial use of interfaces, information hiding, and polymorphism, and they often introduce a level of indirection in a clever way. Because the patterns add extra classes, associations, and method calls, they sometimes can seem overly complicated. This complexity improves modularity, even at the expense of other quality attributes such as performance or ease of development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, design patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For this reason, the patterns are useful only in situations where the extra flexibility is worth the extra cost required to implement them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Therac-25 accidents highlight several important lessons for design in safety-critical systems.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe the machine, the accidents, and the software issues in great detail, and their article should be required reading for systems and software engineers who design and build safety-critical systems.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Key lessons learned include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process, including early standards and evaluation of intermediate products.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Software quality assurance practices should be an integral part of the development process. These practices should include standards that are set early and used to evaluate intermediate products.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Documentation should be done as development progresses, not afterward.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults rather than coding faults, emphasizing the importance of correct and complete requirements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They point out that most computer-related accidents result from requirements faults, not from coding faults",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Safety analysis techniques such as failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA), fault-tree analysis, and detailed code inspections are crucial to identify hazards and prevent accidents.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Atomic Energy of Canada Limited (AECL) performed a safety analysis of the Therac25 system. AECL began with a failure modes and effects analysis to identify single failures leading to significant hazards. Then, to identify multiple failures and quantify the results, it performed a fault-tree analysis. Finally, it hired an outside consultant to perform detailed code inspections of the software functions related to the most serious hazards",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Hardware interlocks should be used to back up software control to prevent hazardous failures.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The AECL final report recommended 10 changes to the Therac-25 hardware, including interlocks to back up software control of energy selection and electron-beam scanning.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Timing errors can be difficult to reproduce but can cause serious accidents, so special attention must be paid to timing and concurrency issues.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Leveson and Turner (1993) describe how the underlying cause of the problems was a timing error that was difficult to reproduce.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The Object-Oriented characteristics of encapsulation and information hiding support reuse by providing considerable flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and in modifying and reusing designs.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Both the separation of object instances from instance variables and of interfaces from class definitions give us considerable flexibility in encapsulating design decisions and in modifying and reusing designs.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Encapsulation supports reuse through object composition, where a composite class manipulates its object-based attributes only by using their interfaces, allowing easy replacement of one class component with another as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An advantage of object composition is its support of modularity; the composite class knows nothing about the implementations of its object-based attributes and can manipulate these attributes only by using their interfaces. As such, we can easily replace one class component with another, as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Inheritance, another Object-Oriented characteristic, supports reuse by allowing new classes to be built by extending or modifying definitions of existing classes, thereby reusing and adding to the definitions of an existing class.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Alternatively, we can build new classes by extending or modifying definitions of existing classes. This kind of construction, called inheritance, defines a new class by directly reusing (and adding to) the definitions of an existing class.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Criteria to decide whether to reuse a class in a new system include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An advantage of object composition is its support of modularity; the composite class knows nothing about the implementations of its object-based attributes and can manipulate these attributes only by using their interfaces. As such, we can easily replace one class component with another, as long as the replacement complies with the same interface.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Whether the class's interface matches the required functionality and can be used without modification (black-box reuse).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We perform black-box reuse often, when we use routines from mathematical libraries or build graphical interfaces from predefined sets of components.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Whether the class can be modified easily to fit particular needs (clear-box reuse), with the effort to understand and modify the component being less than the effort to write a new equivalent component.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Clear-box reuse (sometimes called white-box reuse) is more common but still controversial, because the effort to understand and modify the component must be less than the effort to write a new equivalent component.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Whether the class supports modularity and can be replaced or extended without affecting other parts of the system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "An advantage of object composition is its support of modularity; the composite class knows nothing about the implementations of its object-based attributes and can manipulate these attributes only by using their interfaces.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is useful to have separate phases for system and program design because program designers become deeply involved with the details of the code and may sometimes neglect the larger picture of how the system should work.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "For similar reasons, it is useful for program designers to be different from system designers. Program designers become deeply involved with the details of the code, and they sometimes neglect the larger picture of how the system should work.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Separating these roles allows for techniques such as walkthroughs, inspections, and reviews to bring the two types of designers together to double-check the design before coding, as well as to provide continuity in the development process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We will see in later chapters that techniques such as walkthroughs, inspections, and reviews can bring the two types of designers together to double-check the design before it goes on to be coded, as well as to provide continuity in the development process.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important if two different terms are being used to refer to the same entity because this can lead to confusion and inconsistency in the use cases, making it harder to clearly specify and understand the system behavior from the user's perspective.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Use cases are used to specify user views of essential system behavior. They model only system functionality that can be initiated by some actor in the environment.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Each use case identifies pre-conditions and alternative behavior if the pre-conditions are not met, such as looking for a lost book; post-conditions, which summarize the effects of the use case; and a normal, error-free scenario comprising a sequence of steps performed by actors or by the system.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Using different terms for the same entity can obscure the understanding of the actors and their interactions with the system, which is critical since use cases focus on the interactions initiated by actors and the system's responses.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Use cases model only system functionality that can be initiated by some actor in the environment.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
