        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The likely benefits of using inheritance in this case include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Code reuse by inheriting common attributes and methods from the general sale item class, reducing duplication.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Any Bulk Sale object will comprise attributes and methods defined in the parent Sale class together with those defined in the Bulk Sale class.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Ability to specialize or override methods in subclasses to handle service-specific behavior, such as calculating costs differently for book purchases versus rebinding.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "How the cost is calculated (i.e., which method is executed and whether a discount is applied) will depend on whether the object is an ordinary Sale or a Bulk Sale.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Polymorphism allows code to interact with sale items through a common interface, while the actual behavior depends on the specific subclass instance at runtime.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Objects of different types may react to the same message by producing type-specific responses. Designers and programmers need not know the exact types of the objects that the polymorphic code is manipulating.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, there are arguments against using inheritance in this case, and factors that could influence the decision.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "Possible arguments against using inheritance include:",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance can lead to tight coupling between the parent and child classes, making changes in the parent class potentially affect all subclasses.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "If the services differ significantly in behavior or attributes, forcing them into a single inheritance hierarchy might complicate the design.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Composition might be a better alternative if the services share some components but have distinct behaviors, allowing more flexible object construction.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In an OO system, there are two main techniques for constructing large objects: inheritance and composition.",
                "img_id": null
            }
