[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The relationship between design and implementation is critical because the design serves as a guide to the function or purpose of each component, while the implementation is the actual coding of that design into a working system.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Programming involves a great deal of creativity. Remember that the design is a guide to the function or purpose of each component, but the programmer has great flexibility in implementing the design as code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is important to match the implementation to the design to ensure that the modularity, low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces specified in the design are carried forward into the code. This correspondence allows the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures to be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The most critical standard is the need for a direct correspondence between the program design components and the program code components. The entire design process is of little value if the design's modularity is not carried forward into the code. Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Matching design and implementation is essential because the system's general purpose may remain the same, but its nature can change over time due to enhancements and modifications. Changes are made first to the high-level design and then traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Without this correspondence, testing, maintenance, and configuration management become impossible.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Remember that the system's general purpose is likely to remain the same throughout the software's lifetime, but its nature may change over time as customers identify enhancements and modifications. ... These changes are made first to the high-level design and then are traced through lower design levels to the code that must be modified. Thus, the correspondence between design and code is essential. In later chapters, we will see that testing, maintenance, and configuration management are impossible without the links established by these standards.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To keep the design and implementation consistent, one should ensure that the design's modularity and characteristics are reflected in the code, maintain clear documentation, and use standards and procedures that facilitate tracing and modifying code according to design changes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Design characteristics, such as low coupling, high cohesion, and well-defined interfaces, should also be program characteristics, so that the algorithms, functions, interfaces, and data structures can be traced easily from design to code and back again.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The entire design process is of little value if the design's modularity is not carried forward into the code.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The kind of reuse where you use components originally developed for other projects is called consumer reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "There are two kinds of reuse: producer reuse, where we are creating components designed to be reused in subsequent applications, and consumer reuse, where we are using components that were originally developed for other projects (Barnes and Bollinger 1991).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Problems encountered in reuse include conflicts in reuse goals between different management levels, difficulties in measuring reuse success, and social, cultural, and legal issues that make reuse seem radical and threatening to developers accustomed to writing software from scratch.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse goals can conflict, and management must resolve conflicts early and clearly. For example, as shown in Figure 12.7, a division manager's reuse goal may conflict with a project manager's goal, so no reuse ever gets done.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Moreover, reuse often seems radical and threatening to developers who are accustomed to writing software from scratch. It is clear that many social, cultural, and legal issues are involved in reuse, as well as technical ones.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "led to the generation of over 100 possible measurements-clearly, an unacceptable number of measurements to make.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "These problems were resolved by establishing clear management commitment, selecting appropriate target domains, systematic development of reusable modules based on domain analysis, and investing several years of continuous effort in reuse.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "They found that their critical success factors were (Isoda 1992) - senior management commitment - selecting appropriate target domains - systematic development of reusable modules based on domain analysis - investing several years of continuous effort in reuse.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Guidelines that may help eliminate or mitigate problems include making reuse goals measurable, resolving conflicts in reuse goals early and clearly, understanding different perspectives and priorities of participants in the reuse program, and deciding organizationally who pays for reuse, who owns reusable components, and who builds and maintains them.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse goals should be measurable, so that we can tell if we have met them.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Reuse goals can conflict, and management must resolve conflicts early and clearly.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Different perspectives may generate different questions. Whereas programmers ask specific technical questions, such as 'Is this sort routine written in C ++ ?' a vice-president is focused on the corporation as a whole and its position in the marketplace, asking, 'Are we saving money yet?' Even when the questions are basically the same, we may get different answers. Different points of view reflect the different priorities of the participants in the reuse program.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Every organization must decide at what level certain key questions are asked and answered. For example: Who pays for reuse? When expenses are incurred on one project in the hope that they will be recouped on future projects, they must reflect corporate choice and intent. And who owns the reusable components? Some level determines who owns them and who is responsible for their maintenance. Who builds the components? Another level must be responsible for the construction, population, and support of reuse libraries, as well as the measurement data generated by them.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

