[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "To examine faults from code you have written, first identify the type of fault according to the IBM Orthogonal Defect Classification scheme presented in Table 8.1. This classification includes fault types such as Function, Interface, Checking, Assignment, Timing/serialization, Build/package/merge, Documentation, and Algorithm.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "TABLE 8.1, 1 = IBMOrthogonal Defect Classification. FaultType, 1 = Meaning. Function, 1 = Fault that affects capability, end-user interfaces, product interfaces, interface with hardware architecture, or global data structure. Interface, 1 = Fault in interacting with other components or drivers via calls, macros, control blocks, or parameter lists. Checking, 1 = Fault in program logic that fails to validate data and values properly before they are used. Assignment, 1 = Fault in data structure or code block initialization. Timing/serialization, 1 = Fault that involves timing of shared and real-time resources. Build/package/merge, 1 = Fault that occurs because of problems in repositories,management changes, or version control. Documentation, 1 = Fault that affects publications and maintenance notes. Algorithm, 1 = Fault involving efficiency or correctness of algorithm or data structure but not design",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Next, classify each fault using the orthogonal defect classification approach, which requires that each fault belongs to exactly one category to maintain clarity and meaningful measurement. Additionally, classify the fault as either a fault of omission (something missing, e.g., a variable not initialized) or a fault of commission (something incorrect, e.g., variable initialized to the wrong value).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One of the key features of orthogonal defect classification is its orthogonality. That is, a classification scheme is orthogonal if any item being classified belongs to exactly one category. In other words, we want to track the faults in our system in an unambiguous way, so that the summary information about the number of faults in each class is meaningful.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "When using the classification, the developers identify not only the type of fault, but also whether it is a fault of omission or commission. A fault of omission is one that results when some key aspect of the code is missing; for example, a fault may occur when a variable is not initialized. A fault of commission is one that is incorrect; for example, the variable is initialized to the wrong value.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The IBM defect classification is product- and organization-independent and applicable to all stages of development, making it a useful tool for tracking and analyzing faults to improve the development process.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Thus, the classification scheme must be product- and organization-independent, and be applicable to all stages of development.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Difficulties encountered in classifying faults may include ambiguity in determining the exact category a fault belongs to if the fault could potentially fit into more than one category, which violates the orthogonality principle. Ensuring consistent classification between different developers can also be challenging.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We lose the meaning of the measurements if a fault might belong to more than one class. In the same way, the fault classification must be clear, so that any two developers are likely to classify a particular fault in the same way.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

