[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Object-oriented testing differs from traditional testing in several key ways related to the nature of objects, encapsulation, inheritance, and the interactions among components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways. First, she notes which aspects of object orientation make testing easier and which make it harder.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "The main differences between object-oriented and traditional testing include",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Graham (1996a) summarizes the differences between object-oriented and traditional testing in two ways.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Unit testing is less difficult in object-oriented systems because objects tend to be small and complexity is often pushed toward interfaces among components.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "objects tend to be small, and the complexity that might ordinarily reside in the component is often pushed instead toward the interfaces among components. This difference means that unit testing is less difficult",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Integration testing must be more extensive in object-oriented systems due to encapsulation isolating components and the interactions among objects.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "encapsulation is often considered a positive attribute of object-oriented design, but it also requires more extensive integration testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Inheritance introduces the need for more testing, especially if inherited functions are redefined, have specific behavior in derived classes, or need to be consistent with other functions in the class.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Similarly, inheritance introduces the need for more testing. An inherited function needs additional testing if it is redefined, it has a specific behavior in a derived class, other functions in that class are supposed to be consistent",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis require special treatment in object-oriented testing because traditional tools and metrics are often inadequate for objects and methods.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "requirements analysis and validation, test case generation, source code analysis, and coverage analysis require special treatment. The farther the gray line is out from the center of the diagram, the more the difference between object-oriented and traditional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "most tools that assist in test case generation are not prepared to handle a model expressed in objects and methods.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Most source code measurements are defined for procedural code, not for objects and methods. Traditional metrics such as cyclomatic numbers are of little use when assessing the size and complexity of object-oriented systems.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Because it is the interaction of objects that is the source of complexity, code coverage measurements and tools are of less value in object-oriented testing than in traditional testing.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Additionally, testing object-oriented systems requires retesting inherited methods when subclasses override them or when new subclasses are added, unlike traditional testing where existing test data can often be reused without modification.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "when a subclass replaces an inherited method with a locally defined method with the same name, the overriding subclass must be retested, and probably with a different set of test data.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "when we add a new subclass or modify an existing subclass, we must retest the methods inherited from each of its ancestor superclasses.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

