[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The principles of Cleanroom software development include separation of the development and test teams, reliance on peer review instead of unit testing, use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design, and statistical testing based on operational scenarios.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The cleanroom process was tailored, based on the results of the two experiments, so that it involved - separation of the development and test teams - reliance on peer review instead of unit testing - use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design - statistical testing based on operational scenarios",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom shifts effort from coding to design, with developers spending about half their time writing code and half reading it, compared to traditional developers who spend 85% of their time coding and 15% reading. This approach increases productivity and decreases rework.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Basili and Green (1994) found that 6% of project effort shifted from coding to design when cleanroom was used. Also, whereas traditional developers spent 85% of their time writing code and 15% reading it, the cleanroom team spent about half its time on each activity. Productivity increased by 50% and the amount of rework decreased.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Cleanroom differs from conventional testing in that it relies on statistical testing based on operational scenarios rather than extensive unit testing, and emphasizes peer review and formal design methods over traditional testing practices.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The cleanroom process was tailored, based on the results of the two experiments, so that it involved - separation of the development and test teams - reliance on peer review instead of unit testing - use of informal state machines and functions to define the system design - statistical testing based on operational scenarios",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, cleanroom participants often had difficulty using formal methods, were uncomfortable with being unable to compile their code, and had difficulty coordinating developers and testers.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Cleanroom participants did not like using design abstractions and box structures, were uncomfortable with being unable to compile their code, and had difficulty coordinating developers and testers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, conventional testing typically involves developers performing unit testing themselves, and may not emphasize formal design methods or statistical testing based on operational profiles.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The cleanroom process was tailored, based on the results of the two experiments, so that it involved - separation of the development and test teams - reliance on peer review instead of unit testing",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

