        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "If the organization can control who uses Z and when, an experiment would be preferable because the results are usually more generalizable and allow for direct manipulation of variables.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One key motivator for using a formal experiment rather than a case study or survey is that the results of an experiment are usually more generalizable.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "If control over variables is limited, a case study would be more appropriate, documenting the results in the context of the organization's typical projects and environment.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "If we have no control over who is using which design method, then we do a case study to document the results.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The confidence the organization can have in the results depends on the type of study: experiments provide more generalizable and reliable results, while case studies provide context-specific insights but may be less generalizable.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
