[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Vic Basili's 1997 paper on software reading describes a series of studies that each contributed knowledge about the use of software reading technology in particular environments, using different types of studies for different goals.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In a 1997 paper, Vic Basili describes a series of studies of a particular kind of software technology, called software reading. (V. Basili (1997). “Evolving and packaging reading techniques.” Journal of Systems and Software, 38: 3 - 12.) Each study in the series contributed some knowledge about the use of this technology in a particular environment. A number of different types of studies were used: Some studies looked at whether or not the technology was feasible in the environment, other studies tested very specific hypotheses about the technology, and still other studies examined the use of the technology in detail.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For the goal of determining whether the technology is feasible in the environment, I would recommend feasibility studies that assess the practicality and initial acceptance of software reading in the specific organizational context.",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For testing very specific hypotheses about the technology, controlled experiments or hypothesis-driven studies should be conducted to rigorously evaluate particular aspects or effects of software reading.",
        "citations": []
    },
